[[Croatia]] uses the [[dmy|day-month-year]] date notation and both the [[24-hour clock|24-hour]] and the [[12-hour clock]] for expressing time of day.
== Date == In [[Croatian language]], dates are written using the day-month-year format. The month can be spelled out in lower case (e.g. ''{{nowrap|17. ožujka 2018.}}'' for 17 March 2018) or represented by an Arabic or Roman [[ordinal number (linguistics)|ordinal number]] (''{{nowrap|17. 3. 2018.}}'', ''{{nowrap|17. III. 2018.}}''). Ordinal numbers are always followed by a [[full stop]] and separated by spaces. The [[genitive case]] is used for the month name (implies e.g. ''17. [dan] ožujka'' "the 17th [day] of March"), but the [[nominative case]] (e.g. ''17. ožujak 2018.'') is also often seen in (incorrect) colloquial use.<ref name="orthography full stop">{{cite web |title=8.2. Točka - Hrvatski pravopis |url=http://pravopis.hr/pravilo/tocka/55/ |website=Pravopis.hr |accessdate=1 November 2018 |language=hr}}</ref><ref name="rtl date">{{cite web |title=Pisanje datuma: znate li kako se ispravno pišu datumi? |url=https://zivotistil.rtl.hr/edukacija/2639937/pisanje-datuma-znate-li-kako-se-ispravno-pisu-datumi/ |website=[[RTL Televizija|RTL.hr]] |accessdate=1 November 2018 |language=hr |date=22 February 2017}}</ref><ref name="bujica rijeci">{{cite web |last1=Šćuric |first1=Dejana |title=Zapisivanje datuma ili nadnevka |url=http://bujicarijeci.com/2012/07/zapisivanje-datuma-ili-nadnevka/ |website=Bujicarijeci.com |accessdate=1 November 2018 |language=hr |date=17 July 2012}}</ref>
''17. ožujka'' should be spoken ''sedamnaesti ožujka'' ("the 17th of March", using nominative) or ''sedamnaestog ožujka'' ("on the 17th of March", using genitive).<ref name="bujica rijeci"/><ref name="rtl date"/> [[Leading zero]]es in dates should be omitted in non-technical situations, and the names of months and days of week are only capitalised at the beginning of a sentence.<ref name="orthography full stop"/><ref name="bujica rijeci"/><ref name="rtl date"/> The week starts on Monday, while the weekend consists of Saturday and Sunday.
{{col-begin|width=50em}} {{col-3}} {| class="wikitable" style="width:15em" |+ Names of months ! English !! Croatian |- | January || siječanj |- | February || veljača |- | March || ožujak |- | April || travanj |- | May || svibanj |- | June || lipanj |} {{col-3}} {| class="wikitable" style="width:15em" |+ &nbsp; ! English !! Croatian |- | July || srpanj |- | August || kolovoz |- | September || rujan |- | October || listopad |- | November || studeni |- | December || prosinac |} {{col-3}} {| class="wikitable" style="width:15em" |+ Days of week ! English !! Croatian |- | Monday || ponedjeljak |- | Tuesday || utorak |- | Wednesday || srijeda |- | Thursday || četvrtak |- | Friday || petak |- | Saturday || subota |- | Sunday || nedjelja |} {{col-end}}
== Time == In formal and [[written language]], the time of day is usually expressed using the [[24-hour clock]]. Hours and minutes are separated using either a colon or a full stop. Leading zeroes should only be used for minutes, except in tables, on electronic displays etc.<ref name="orthography colon">{{cite web |title=8.19.2. Znak za odjeljivanje sati i minuta - Hrvatski pravopis |url=http://pravopis.hr/pravilo/znak-za-odjeljivanje-sati-i-minuta/77/ |website=Pravopis.hr |accessdate=1 November 2018 |language=hr}}</ref> In informal use, especially in [[spoken language|speech]], the [[12-hour clock]] is used. However, instead of the English "a.m."/"p.m." system, descriptive phrases are used in cases of ambiguity, e.g. ''ujutro'' "in the morning", ''prijepodne'' "before noon", ''poslijepodne'' "afternoon", ''navečer'' "in the evening".
