pe]]. |- | 1819 || [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]] || [[North Carolina]] || [[United States]] | |- | 1819 || [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]] || [[Alabama]] || [[United States]] || State capital, grew from the 1540 French settlement [[Fort Toulouse]]. |- | 1819 || [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]] || [[Illinois]] || [[United States]] | |- | 1819 || [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] || [[Tennessee]] || [[United States]] || Near the site of the earlier French [[Fort Prudhomme]]. |- | 1819 || [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] || [[Alabama]] || [[United States]] || |- | 1820 || [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]] || [[Indiana]] || [[United States]] || Formerly named Big St. Joseph Station. |- | 1820 || [[Hastings, Minnesota#History|Oliver's Grove]] || [[Minnesota]] || [[United States]] || Near the confluence of the Mississippi, St. Croix, and Vermillion Rivers. In 1820, Oliver's Grove was established as a Trading Post community and a military detachment sent from Fort Snelling. However, until the Treaty of Mendota (1851), the community could not officially be noted for white settlement. In 1857, a year before Minnesota's admission to the union, the area was surveyed and incorporated as the city of Hastings and named the county seat of Dakota County. |- | 1821 || [[Alexandria, British Columbia|Alexandria]] || [[British Columbia]] || [[Canada]] || Grew from fur trading posts of Fort Alexandria, founded by the [[North West Company]] in 1821.<ref>{{BCGNIS|754|Alexandria}}</ref> |- | 1821 || [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]] || [[Connecticut]] || [[United States]] | |- | 1821 || [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] || [[Arkansas]] || [[United States]] | |- | 1821 || [[Indianapolis, Indiana|Indianapolis]] || [[Indiana]] || [[United States]] | |- | 1822 | [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] | [[Florida]] | [[United States]] | |- | 1822 || [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]] || [[Mississippi]] || [[United States]] | |- | 1823 || [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] || 