{{for|the Royal Navy intelligence organization|Room 39 (Royal Navy)}} {{multiple| {{pov|date=June 2018}} {{refimprove|date=June 2018}} {{update|date=June 2018}} }} {{Coord|39.016758|125.740979|display=title}} {{Infobox government agency | agency_name = Room 39 | type = agency | nativename = | nativename_a = | nativename_r = | logo = | logo_width = | logo_caption = | seal = | seal_width = | seal_caption = | picture = | picture_width = | picture_caption = | formed = Late 1970s | preceding1 = | preceding2 = <!-- (etc.) --> | dissolved = | superseding = | jurisdiction = | headquarters = Pyongyang, North Korea | coordinates = | motto = | employees = | budget = | prime_minister_name = | minister1_name = | minister1_pfo = | minister2_name = | minister2_pfo = <!-- (etc.) --> | deputyminister1_name = | deputyminister1_pfo = | deputyminister2_name = | deputyminister2_pfo = <!-- (etc.) --> | chief1_name = | chief1_position = | chief2_name = | chief2_position = <!-- (etc.) --> | director_general = | agency_type = | parent_department = | parent_agency = [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]] | child1_agency = | child2_agency = <!-- (etc.) --> | keydocument1 = <!-- (etc.) --> | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | footnotes = | map = | map_width = | map_caption = }} {{Infobox Korean name | hangul = 삼십구호실 | hanja = 三十九號室 | rr = Samsipgu-hosil | mr = Samsipku-hosil | context = north }}
'''Room 39''' (officially '''Central Committee Bureau 39 of the Workers' Party of Korea''',<ref name="forb_KimJ">{{Cite web | title = Kim Jong Il's 'Cashbox' | last = Rosett | first = Claudia | work = Forbes | date = 15 April 2010 | accessdate = 2015-07-09 | url = https://www.forbes.com/2010/04/15/kim-jong-il-north-korea-opinions-columnists-claudia-rosett.html }}</ref> also referred to as '''Bureau 39''', '''Division 39''', or '''Office 39'''<ref name="Landler">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/31/world/asia/31diplo.html?partner=rss&emc=rss | work=The New York Times | title=New U.S. Sanctions Aim at North Korean Elite | first=Mark | last=Landler | date=August 30, 2010}}</ref>) is a secretive [[North Korea]]n party organization that seeks ways to maintain the foreign currency [[slush fund]] for [[Leaders of North Korea|the country's leaders]], initially [[Kim Il-sung]], then, in progression, [[Kim Jong-il]] and [[Kim Jong-un]].<ref name=vf>{{cite web|title=North Korea's Dollar Store|date=August 5, 2009 |author=David Rose|work=Vanity Fair|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/politics/features/2009/09/office-39-200909?printable=true}}</ref>{{not in source|date=June 2018}}
The organization is estimated to bring in between $500 million and $1 billion per year or more<ref name="vf111">{{cite news|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/style/2009/09/office-39-200909|title=North Korea’s Dollar Store|last=Rose|first=David|date=September 2009|work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> and may be involved in [[North Korea's illicit activities|illegal activities]], such as [[Superdollar|counterfeiting $100 bills]], producing controlled substances (including the synthesis of [[methamphetamine]] and the conversion of [[morphine]]-containing [[opium]] into more potent opiates like [[heroin]]), and international insurance fraud.<ref name=vf/><ref name=wp>{{Cite news|title=Global Insurance Fraud By North Korea Outlined|newspaper=Washington Post|date=June 18, 2009 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/17/AR2009061703852_pf.html}}</ref>
Although the seclusion of the North Korean state makes it difficult to evaluate this kind of information, many claim that Room 39 is critical to [[Kim Jong-un]]'s continued power, enabling him to buy political support and help fund [[North Korean nuclear weapons program|North Korea's nuclear weapons program]].<ref name=vf/>
Room 39 is the largest of three influential so-called Third Floor offices along with [[Office 35]] tasked with intelligence and [[Office 38]] which handles legal financial activities.{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=178}} Room 39 is believed to be located inside a ruling [[Workers' Party of Korea|Workers' Party]] building in [[Pyongyang]],<ref name="Nkorea2008">{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Kelly Olsen|title=New sanctions could hit North Korea's fundraising|url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/ci_12566697|date=June 11, 2009}}</ref> not far from one of the [[Residences of North Korean leaders|North Korean leader's residences]].<ref name="Landler"/> All three Offices were initially housed on the third floor of the building where Kim Jong-il's office used to be, hence the moniker "Third Floor".{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=178}}
==History== Room 39 was established by Kim Il-sung in the late 1970s.{{fact|date=June 2018}} It has been described as the linchpin of the North's so-called "court economy" centered on the dynastic Kim family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/World/20100204/nkorea_room39_100204/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120723144454/http://www.ctv.ca/CTVNews/World/20100204/nkorea_room39_100204/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=July 23, 2012|title=North Korea fires head of secret bureau 'Room 39'|work=CTV News|date=Feb 4, 2010}}</ref>
According to Kim Kwang-jin, in 1972, Kim Jong-il created the central party department called "Office No. 39", which was named after the arbitrary office number where it began operations.<ref name="The Defector’s Tale: Inside North Korea’s Secret Economy">{{cite web | url=http://www.worldaffairsjournal.org/article/defector%E2%80%99s-tale-inside-north-korea%E2%80%99s-secret-economy | title=The Defector’s Tale: Inside North Korea’s Secret Economy | publisher=World Affairs | accessdate=12 September 2017 | author=Kim Kwang Jin}}</ref> Initially the Office was under the [[Finance and Accounting Department]] of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]].{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=179}}
In early 2010, [[South Korea]]'s [[Yonhap|Yonhap news agency]] reported that Kim Dong-un, head of the department, was replaced by his deputy, Jon Il-chun.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/feb/03/report-nkorea-fires-director-of-kims-finances/|title=Report: NKorea Fires Director of Kim's Finances|publisher=AP|date=February 4, 2010}}</ref>
The ''[[The Chosun Ilbo|Chosun Ilbo]]'' reported that [[Room 38]], led by [[Kim Jong-il]], was merged into Room 39 in late 2009, but the two were split again in 2010 due to difficulties in obtaining foreign currency.<ref name="ChosunIlbo">{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/06/22/2010062201162.html|work=Chosun Ilbo|title=Kim Jong-il Restores Special Department to Swell Coffers|date=June 22, 2010}}</ref> Room 38 handles funds of the [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)|Kim family]] in legal businesses and acts as a [[front organization]] for Room 39.{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=178}}
In July 2017, Chon Il-chun, first vice department director of the party’s Central Committee and a former classmate of Kim Jong-il was leader of the office.<ref name="Ri Jong Ho, high-level defector and former official in Office 39, says North Korea gets much more oil from Russia than previously known">{{cite web | url=http://www.nkeconwatch.com/category/dprk-organizations/companies/daesung-trading-company/ | title=Ri Jong Ho, high-level defector and former official in Office 39, says North Korea gets much more oil from Russia than previously known | publisher=Archive for the ‘Daesung Trading Company’ Category - | accessdate=13 September 2017 | author=Benjamin Katzeff Silberstein}}</ref>
==Purpose and activities== Room 39 is also involved in the management of foreign currency earnings from foreigners' hotels in Pyongyang, gold and zinc mining, and agricultural and fisheries exports. They are believed to run networks of illegal and legal companies that often change names.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/world/hotel-of-doom-takes-kims-illusion-building-sky-high-0txmm66fh|title=‘Hotel of Doom’ takes Kim’s illusion-building sky high|last=Sherwell|first=Philip|date=2017-08-06|work=The Times|access-date=2017-08-06|language=en|subscription=Y}}</ref> Companies, which used to number 120 at one point,{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=179}} believed to be controlled by Room 39 include [[Zokwang Trading]] and [[Taesong Bank]].<ref name="ChosunIlbo"/> Many of the $500 million worth of textiles North Korea exports each year have phony "made in China" labels attached to them and the wages of the estimated 50,000 North Korean workers sent abroad to work are reported to have added $500 million to $2 billion a year to Room 39's income.<ref name=":1" />
A 2007 report published by the Millennium Project of the World Federation of United Nations Associations said North Korea makes an estimated $500 million to $1 billion annually from illegal enterprises.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kelly | last = Olsen | title= North Korea's secret: Room 39|date = June 11, 2009| url=http://www.sltrib.com/ci_12566697}}</ref> Criminal operations reported to be run by Room 39 include trafficking fake US dollars, peddling bogus [[VIAGRA|Viagra]], exporting the recreational drug [[Methamphetamine|N-methylamphetamine]] and obtaining Russian oil using dealers in Singapore.<ref name=":1" /> At some point, transactions and trade by Office 39 reached 25 to 50% of the total of North Korea.{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=179}}{{clarification needed|date=June 2018}}
In 2009, a ''[[Washington Post]]'' report outlined a global insurance fraud scheme by the North Korean government. The state-owned Korea National Insurance Corp (KNIC) sought [[reinsurance]] contracts with international reinsurers and then submitted fraudulent claims; the contracts were governed by North Korean law and legal challenges were fruitless.<ref name=wp/> Document forgeries are also reported.{{sfn|Fischer|2016|p=180}}
Room 39 is also believed to be operating the overseas North Korean restaurant chain called ''[[Pyongyang (restaurant chain)|Pyongyang]]''.<ref name="Strangio 2010">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2247402|title=Kingdom Kim's Culinary Outposts: Inside the bizarre world of Asia's North Korean restaurant chain.|last=Strangio|first=Sebastian|date=March 22, 2010|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref>
In 2015, the [[European Union]] placed the KNIC under sanctions and added that the KNIC had links to Office 39.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/apr/23/uk-freezes-assets-of-north-korean-company-in-south-london-insurance-nuclear-weapons|title=UK freezes assets of North Korean company based in south London|last=Booth|first=Robert|date=2017-04-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-04-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The KNIC (which had offices in Hamburg, Germany and London, UK) was reported to have had assets of UK £787 million in 2014 and had been involved in scamming insurance markets and making investments in property and foreign exchange.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/edition/news/kim-cooked-up-nuclear-cash-in-the-suburbs-north-korea-znp25pw5k|title=Kim cooked up ‘nuclear cash’ in the suburbs|last=Gadher|first=Dipesh|date=2017-04-23|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2017-04-23|language=en|subscription=Y}}</ref> [[Thae Yong-ho]], a North Korean diplomat who defected in 2016, said that North Korea earned each year "tens of millions of dollars" with insurance fraud.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/secrets-of-kims-little-house-in-the-suburbs-ksjz9tv65|title=Secrets of Kim’s little house in the suburbs|last=Gadher|first=Dipesh|date=2017-04-23|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2017-04-23|language=en|subscription=Y}}</ref>
Ri Jong-ho was a senior official in the Room 39 organisation for about 30 years. He defected to South Korea in 2014 and to the United States in 2016. Ri was chairman of Korea Kumgang Group, that formed a joint venture with a Chinese businessman to run a taxi company in Pyongyang,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-taxis-idUSKCN0S316T20151009|title=Taxis parade once-empty streets of North Korean capital|last=Pearson|first=James|date=2015-10-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-07-13}}</ref> the president of a North Korean shipping company and head of a Chinese branch of Daeheung, a North Korean trading company involved in seafood, coal, shipping and oil. In a 2017 newspaper article Ri described how he evaded sanctions by transferring cash from China to North Korea by ship and by train.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/he-ran-north-koreas-secret-money-making-operation-now-he-lives-in-virginia/2017/07/12/4cb9a590-6584-11e7-94ab-5b1f0ff459df_story.html|title=He ran North Korea’s secret moneymaking operation. Now he lives in Virginia.|last=Fifield|first=Anna|date=2017-07-13|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-07-13}}</ref>
Some scholars argue that the [[Kaesong Industrial Complex]] is a front to fund Room 39.<ref>http://freekorea.us/#sthash.Z2uNt5cq.dpbs</ref>{{failed verification|date=June 2018}}
